            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <p>The venerable M. Von Humboldt lately wrote to<lb break="yes"/>a Parisian publisher, declining to prepare a revised<lb break="yes"/>edition of his works, and prophesying his own death<lb break="yes"/>as an event which would occur in the year 1859.<lb break="yes"/>This letter was produced in Court recently during<lb break="yes" />the course of a trial in Paris. M. Von Humboldt<lb break="yes"/>added that he preferred that his works should not<lb break="yes"/>be altered until after his death. Last month he<lb break="yes"/>wrote the following letter to the Duke of Saxe-<lb break="no"/>Weimar, declining an invitation to be present at<lb break="yes"/>the Third Centennial Anniversary of the Univer-<lb break="no"/>sity of Jena, in consequence of the weight of bodily<lb break="yes"/>infirmity. The closing part of the letter is a strik<lb break="yes"/>ing evidence of the unquenchable spirit of the<lb break="yes"/>venerable <hi rendition="#i">sevant:</hi>
            </p>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <div n="2">
                <dateline>
                    <hi rendition="#et">
                        <hi rendition="#k">Berlin,</hi> Aug. 10, 1858.</hi>
                </dateline>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>Your Magnificence having, in your own name<lb break="yes"/>and in the name of the highly-honored Senate of<lb break="yes"/>the Grand Ducal and Ducal Saxon united Univer-<lb break="no"/>sity, favored me with an invitation to appear as an<lb break="yes"/>honored guest at the glorious, genuine Protestant<lb break="yes"/>Jubilee of the 15th August, I have delayed writing<lb break="yes"/>to express my deep gratitude till now, almost flat-<lb break="no"/>tering myself, in my 89th year, with the hope that<lb break="yes"/>I might transgress the orders of my physicians, re-<lb break="no"/>quiring me to remain quiet and without change.<lb break="yes" />My wishes have not been fulfilled. Not my labori-<lb break="no"/>ousness, not the interest which I take in the free<lb break="yes"/>public intellectual life of Germany, but my physical<lb break="yes"/>powers, are rapidly declining, and I must deny my-<lb break="no"/>self the privilege of going where I am drawn by<lb break="yes"/>pleasant and suggestive recollections and feelings of<lb break="yes"/>the deepest gratitude.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>Most respectfully, and commending myself to your<lb break="yes"/>favor. I remain. your most obedient colleague.</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rendition="#et">ALEXANDER V. HUMBOLDT.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
            <lb break="yes"/>
